AirBnB Price Prediction¶

This project utilizes the AirBnB Major Cities dataset acquired from: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/rudymizrahi/airbnb-listings-in-major-us-cities-deloitte-ml

We will explore some important trends within the data and pick out important features for predicting a listing price. These prediction models are useful for a host looking to put up a new listing. The models suggest a listing price based on previous listings.

Feature Engineering¶

We'll first extract useful features from the amenities column. Each amenity will be encoded as its own feature. However, if all listings share a specific amenity, it won't be useful as a feature. The same may be true if most listings share the same amenity. Thus, we will encode all amenities and extract only the significant ones to use as predctors for our model.

Data Splitting¶

In [ ]:
X = data.drop(columns='log_price')
y = data['log_price']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

Model Fitting¶

We'll be experimenting with a few models to see which one fits best with this data. For this assignment, we'll use:

  • Linear Regression
  • Decision Tree
  • Random Forest
  • SVM

Linear Regression¶

We'll start with a simple linear regression experiment to see how well it model performs. I originally decided not to try this algorithm out since I figured it'd be too simple. However, it will help assess whether the extracted features truly carry a linear relationship with the listing price.

In [ ]:
lr = LinearRegression()

lr.fit(X_train, y_train)
train_pred = lr.predict(X_train)
test_pred = lr.predict(X_test)

r2_scores = [r2_score(y_train, train_pred), r2_score(y_test, test_pred)]
mse_scores = [mean_squared_error(y_train, train_pred), mean_squared_error(y_test, test_pred)]

lr_scores = {
    'R2' : r2_scores,
    'MSE' : mse_scores
}
In [ ]:
pd.DataFrame(data = lr_scores, index = ['Train', 'Test'])
Out[ ]:

Linear Regression is clearly not an optimal model to use as a predictor here.

Decision Tree¶

We'll start our series of experiments with a simple tree, tuning its depth with 5-fold cv.

In [ ]:
depth_results = dict()

maxTreeDepth = list(range(1, 16))

for depth in maxTreeDepth:
    cv_results = cross_validate(DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth = depth), X_train, y_train, cv = 5, scoring=('r2', 'neg_mean_squared_error'), return_train_score=True, return_estimator=True)
    depth_results[depth] = cv_results
In [ ]:
r2_results = dict()
mse_results = dict()

for depth in maxTreeDepth:
    r2_results[depth] = [depth_results[depth]['train_r2'].mean(), depth_results[depth]['test_r2'].mean()]
    mse_results[depth] = [depth_results[depth]['train_neg_mean_squared_error'].mean(), depth_results[depth]['test_neg_mean_squared_error'].mean()]
In [ ]:
r2_results = pd.DataFrame(r2_results)
mse_results = pd.DataFrame(mse_results)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,10))

plt.ylabel('R2')

Depth of 8 appears to be the sweet spot for this learning model. Any depth beyond that shows strong evidence of overfitting.

Fitting and evaluating tree w/ depth = 8 on entire training set.

Random Forest¶

We'll be tuning a random forest's number of trees.

In [ ]:
depth_results = dict()

tree_values = list(range(1, 51, 5))

for depth in tree_values:
    cv_results = cross_validate(RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=depth), X_train, y_train, cv = 5, scoring=('r2', 'neg_mean_squared_error'), return_train_score=True)
    depth_results[depth] = cv_results
In [ ]:
r2_results = dict()
mse_results = dict()

for depth in tree_values:
    if depth == 51: break
    r2_results[depth] = [depth_results[depth]['train_r2'].mean(), depth_results[depth]['test_r2'].mean()]
    mse_results[depth] = [depth_results[depth]['train_neg_mean_squared_error'].mean(), depth_results[depth]['test_neg_mean_squared_error'].mean()]

Conclusion¶

Perhaps with a more complext model, we'll be able to improve the performance(Neural Net). On the other hand, the final dataset may be missing important features for a better predictor.
